WEBVTT

00:00:00.530 --> 00:00:08.050
Hello and welcome back. In this new section, I'm going to show you how to use Codex with Frida.

00:00:08.050 --> 00:00:14.050
Frida is a dynamic instrumentation toolkit for developers, reverse engineers,

00:00:14.050 --> 00:00:18.850
and security researchers. And this is the website where you can read more about Frida.

00:00:18.850 --> 00:00:26.160
So the first step is to install Frida. In order to do that, I will use Codex.

00:00:26.160 --> 00:00:33.960
So let's open up Codex first, start the new chat, and close the sidebar, and make

00:00:33.960 --> 00:00:41.660
sure you are using GPT-5.5, which is the highest model at time of recording, and

00:00:41.660 --> 00:00:49.660
set the reasoning effort to extra high. And now let's type in the prompt.

00:00:49.660 --> 00:01:01.740
Install Frida reverse engineering tool for this machine. You may use this folder

00:01:01.740 --> 00:01:12.200
for the Frida project tool. So let's open File Explorer and take a look at

00:01:12.200 --> 00:01:14.600
the C drive.

00:01:14.600 --> 00:01:16.820
We have RADARE2AI.

00:01:16.820 --> 00:01:23.400
So let's create a new folder called Frida_AI

00:01:23.400 --> 00:01:25.080
and open it.

00:01:25.080 --> 00:01:31.420
Let us now copy the path and paste it into the prompt.

00:01:31.420 --> 00:01:34.380
So this will be our prompt to Codex

00:01:34.380 --> 00:01:37.440
to help us install Frida.

00:01:37.440 --> 00:01:40.660
It reads, install Frida reverse engineering tool

00:01:40.660 --> 00:01:41.820
for this machine.

00:01:41.820 --> 00:01:44.900
You may use this folder for the Frida project tool.

00:01:44.900 --> 00:02:00.620
And then, we also say, if you are unsure of anything, don't guess, don't assume, ask me,

00:02:00.620 --> 00:02:02.300
and then click send.

00:02:02.300 --> 00:02:09.440
It replies by saying that it will set up this as a local Frida environment, tool environment

00:02:09.440 --> 00:02:14.960
under this folder and then verify the command line tools run from this machine so it checks

00:02:14.960 --> 00:02:22.000
for the availability of Python. It confirms the virtual environment is in place, and now it is

00:02:22.000 --> 00:02:28.800
going to do the installation. It also helpfully installs a tiny launcher script so that we can

00:02:28.800 --> 00:02:34.880
open a ready-to-use shell without remembering the virtual environment path each time. It is now doing

00:02:34.880 --> 00:02:41.080
some tests, and now it is cleaning up some leftover processes. Finally, it confirms

00:02:41.080 --> 00:02:43.700
that it has completed installation.

00:02:43.700 --> 00:02:51.200
So now we write our skill file, so let's ask it to do that for us.

00:02:51.200 --> 00:03:06.880
Write a skill file in MD format so that in future, if I ask you to analyze a binary and provide

00:03:06.880 --> 00:03:17.260
you with the skill file, you will be able to know how to use Frida.

00:03:17.260 --> 00:03:30.590
If you are unsure of anything, don't guess, don't assume, ask me and click send.

00:03:30.590 --> 00:03:35.390
So we are also using the same workflow when installing new tools.

00:03:35.390 --> 00:03:44.750
Every time you finish installing a new tool, you always ask Codex to write a new skill file.

00:03:44.750 --> 00:03:49.730
It is now doing some checking on the JavaScript API names as well.

00:03:49.730 --> 00:03:54.350
And it now knows enough of the context in order to write a skill file.

00:03:54.350 --> 00:03:57.370
And finally it is now writing the actual skill file.

00:03:57.370 --> 00:04:02.190
So the skill file will be called Frida binary analysis skill.

00:04:02.190 --> 00:04:07.430
It has finally completed writing the standalone Markdown skill file.

00:04:07.430 --> 00:04:10.170
So let's ask it where it saved it to.

00:04:10.170 --> 00:04:15.350
Where did you save the file?

00:04:15.350 --> 00:04:19.970
So let's open it in explorer.

00:04:19.970 --> 00:04:27.010
So this is the location. Let's go there now and copy out the skill file. We can cut it out

00:04:27.650 --> 00:04:42.260
and put it in our skills folder, AI skills, and paste it here. Let us open and read it. Press

00:04:42.260 --> 00:04:50.900
Ctrl+Shift+V to view the preview output. So it reads Frida binary analysis ground rules.

00:04:50.900 --> 00:04:56.580
All right, maybe we don't want this first line, so we delete it. And this first line

00:04:56.580 --> 00:05:02.880
here, we want it to work on any binary. It's not just those that I own, so let's

00:05:02.880 --> 00:05:08.040
delete that. That is not helpful. Press Ctrl+Shift+V again, then Ctrl+S to save

00:05:08.040 --> 00:05:12.960
it. All right, so we just read through this, and if you're

00:05:12.960 --> 00:05:21.810
happy with it, we can confirm this skill file. All right, I think it's fine, so we

00:05:21.810 --> 00:05:27.690
can close this now. So next thing to do is to shut down this virtual

00:05:27.690 --> 00:05:33.950
machine and create a snapshot if you want to. And before you do that, it is

00:05:33.950 --> 00:05:40.470
always a good idea to copy out this new skill into a separate location so

00:05:40.470 --> 00:05:47.250
that in future if you ever do a restore to a previous snapshot you won't lose

00:05:47.250 --> 00:05:53.330
this new skill. So that's all. In this video, we have learned how to use Codex to install this

00:05:53.330 --> 00:05:59.650
new skill on using Frida, and also how to create the skill file. So in future, if you wanted to

00:05:59.650 --> 00:06:08.210
run any binary analysis using Frida, you will point Codex to this skill file, ask it to

00:06:08.210 --> 00:06:16.610
read it first, and then it will know how to use Frida. So in the next lesson, we are going to

00:06:16.610 --> 00:06:24.610
do a practical on using this new skill to analyze a binary. So that's all for this video. Thank you

00:06:24.610 --> 00:06:25.090
for watching

